1
00:00:01,001 --> 00:00:03,321
(BIRDSONG)

2
00:00:13,601 --> 00:00:15,161
Come on.

3
00:00:19,881 --> 00:00:21,481
Got ya.

4
00:00:23,481 --> 00:00:26,121
(CRACKING)

5
00:00:27,961 --> 00:00:30,521
Just a little closer...

6
00:00:33,841 --> 00:00:34,841
(SCREAMS)

7
00:00:38,481 --> 00:00:40,281
TANNOY: Ladies and gentlemen,
we'll be commencing

8
00:00:40,401 --> 00:00:42,641
our descent into Tokyo
in approximately 30 minutes.

9
00:00:42,761 --> 00:00:44,281
Please take a moment
to use the washrooms

10
00:00:44,401 --> 00:00:46,121
and collect up
all your belongings.

11
00:00:46,241 --> 00:00:48,921
Excuse me.
Is this wash bag yours?

12
00:00:49,041 --> 00:00:50,641
I just found it in the aisle.

13
00:00:52,001 --> 00:00:53,721
Yes. Sorry.

14
00:00:53,841 --> 00:00:55,561
I'm so clumsy.

15
00:00:55,681 --> 00:00:58,121
My sister's always having
a go at me for this.

16
00:00:58,241 --> 00:01:00,601
- Thanks.
- No problem at all.

17
00:01:00,721 --> 00:01:02,241
Enjoy your flight.

18
00:01:21,161 --> 00:01:23,841
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

19
00:01:29,401 --> 00:01:31,321
(CRACKING)

20
00:01:33,041 --> 00:01:35,481
(GASPS)

21
00:01:45,601 --> 00:01:47,681
(CAR HORN BLARES)

22
00:01:52,441 --> 00:01:54,361
(GASPS)

23
00:01:57,481 --> 00:02:00,601
I'm at the safe house. How long
for the extraction team?

24
00:02:02,401 --> 00:02:03,881
Just make it fast.

25
00:02:10,001 --> 00:02:12,281
(GENTLE PATTERING)

26
00:02:14,881 --> 00:02:17,801
(CRACKING)

27
00:02:54,841 --> 00:02:57,601
(PLAYERS CALL OUT)

28
00:03:03,041 --> 00:03:06,041
(FOOTAGE SLOWS)

29
00:03:07,681 --> 00:03:09,681
(MUFFLED) Go on, Ryan!

30
00:03:11,241 --> 00:03:12,881
Shoot!

31
00:03:22,121 --> 00:03:24,721
- (NORMAL-SPEED FOOTAGE)
- (PLAYERS JEER AND SHOUT)

32
00:03:24,841 --> 00:03:26,321
(BELL RINGS)

33
00:03:28,961 --> 00:03:30,881
Unlucky, man.

34
00:03:32,761 --> 00:03:34,721
- So, next week?
- Yeah.

35
00:03:36,121 --> 00:03:37,441
Laters.

36
00:03:37,561 --> 00:03:39,401
You can play now, man.

37
00:03:39,521 --> 00:03:41,441
You never used
to step on the court.

38
00:03:41,561 --> 00:03:43,641
I should've got it in.
I'll get it in next time.

39
00:03:43,761 --> 00:03:45,201
You've been sick, though.

40
00:03:45,321 --> 00:03:46,681
Appendicitis, right?

41
00:03:46,801 --> 00:03:48,361
That's why we ain't seen you?

42
00:03:48,481 --> 00:03:51,041
- Oh, yeah, yeah.
- And the hernia before that?

43
00:03:51,161 --> 00:03:52,361
Oh, yeah. That was bad.

44
00:03:52,481 --> 00:03:53,761
And that detached retina?
Pt!

45
00:03:53,881 --> 00:03:55,961
That sounds painful.
You've been so unlucky.

46
00:03:56,081 --> 00:03:57,601
- So unlucky.
- So what, we don't see you

47
00:03:57,721 --> 00:03:59,201
and now you're off travelling?

48
00:03:59,321 --> 00:04:01,241
- Only for a bit.
- Better be.

49
00:04:03,121 --> 00:04:04,641
I've missed you, man.

50
00:04:04,761 --> 00:04:05,921
We all do.

51
00:04:11,361 --> 00:04:12,881
Is there a problem, guys?

52
00:04:13,001 --> 00:04:14,161
WOMAN: Just give me his number.

53
00:04:14,281 --> 00:04:15,401
No!

54
00:04:15,521 --> 00:04:17,361
Alexa, play Rubber Soul.

55
00:04:17,481 --> 00:04:18,961
- Why not?
- Because!

56
00:04:19,081 --> 00:04:21,121
I don't want to give you
his number. I'm packing.

57
00:04:21,241 --> 00:04:23,161
This is the third secondment
you've been selected for.

58
00:04:23,281 --> 00:04:24,961
Is it?
I thought it was the second.

59
00:04:25,081 --> 00:04:26,201
You're not even
going to be here.

60
00:04:26,321 --> 00:04:28,681
And all this
during your probationer period?

61
00:04:28,801 --> 00:04:31,201
I know. It's amazing.

62
00:04:31,321 --> 00:04:33,401
Is his number in here? Oh!

63
00:04:33,521 --> 00:04:34,801
Play Rubber Soul!

64
00:04:34,921 --> 00:04:37,441
ALEXA: The nearest shoe shop
ls 1.2 miles walking distance.

65
00:04:37,561 --> 00:04:38,761
I think it just hates
your voice, Dad.

66
00:04:38,881 --> 00:04:41,921
And your boss is all right
with you being away on this?

67
00:04:42,961 --> 00:04:45,801
Totally.
He's totally all right with it.

68
00:04:45,921 --> 00:04:47,681
I'm not all right
with this, Yaz.

69
00:04:47,801 --> 00:04:50,641
This is your fourth secondment.

70
00:04:50,761 --> 00:04:52,761
Fourth time I get a load
of secretive paperwork,

71
00:04:52,881 --> 00:04:53,921
and you not telling me
anything.

72
00:04:54,041 --> 00:04:55,841
Why do I keep losing
my best probationer?

73
00:04:55,961 --> 00:04:58,321
It's all really good
experience. Honest.

74
00:04:58,441 --> 00:05:00,161
I'm not daft.

75
00:05:00,281 --> 00:05:03,321
Have you had a tap on the
shoulder? Is this undercover?

76
00:05:03,441 --> 00:05:04,561
Sort of.

77
00:05:07,761 --> 00:05:09,201
Last time.

78
00:05:09,321 --> 00:05:12,041
You have to be here
to finish your probation.

79
00:05:12,161 --> 00:05:14,041
I know. I'm coming back,
I promise.

80
00:05:14,161 --> 00:05:16,081
And I presume they're with you?

81
00:05:24,721 --> 00:05:27,241
Four years since
your procedure. Time flies.

82
00:05:27,361 --> 00:05:30,201
- Yeah. Don't it just?
- Test results are all

83
00:05:30,321 --> 00:05:32,561
as they should be,
you'll be pleased to hear.

84
00:05:32,681 --> 00:05:34,401
Any weight fluctuations?

85
00:05:34,521 --> 00:05:35,441
No.

86
00:05:35,561 --> 00:05:37,161
Tiredness?
Muscular aches or pains?

87
00:05:37,281 --> 00:05:38,321
None of that.

88
00:05:39,441 --> 00:05:41,081
I was sorry to hear
about your wife.

89
00:05:41,201 --> 00:05:42,841
Yeah. Thanks.

90
00:05:42,961 --> 00:05:45,641
- We all miss her.
- Yeah.

91
00:05:45,761 --> 00:05:48,321
Right. I don't need to keep you
any longer. Sign on there.

92
00:05:48,441 --> 00:05:50,241
Tick all the boxes.
Data protection.

93
00:05:50,361 --> 00:05:51,281
Right.

94
00:05:51,401 --> 00:05:54,641
- Are you working?
- Um, no. Travelling.

95
00:05:54,761 --> 00:05:56,361
Oh. Anywhere nice?

96
00:05:57,801 --> 00:05:59,681
Sometimes.

97
00:06:10,801 --> 00:06:12,321
(MACHINERY WHIRS)

98
00:06:14,961 --> 00:06:17,441
Ah! There's the blockage.

99
00:06:17,561 --> 00:06:19,041
Oh, sorry! Group message.

100
00:06:19,161 --> 00:06:20,761
Got to concentrate.

101
00:06:20,881 --> 00:06:23,361
Just calling to say hi, fam.
Where are you?

102
00:06:23,481 --> 00:06:26,241
We said an hour. You're late.

103
00:06:26,361 --> 00:06:28,681
Very late.

104
00:06:28,801 --> 00:06:30,201
All of you?

105
00:06:31,521 --> 00:06:33,401
(CAR DOORS OPEN AND CLOSE)

106
00:06:42,481 --> 00:06:45,601
Hi, fellas.
Rocking the ominous look.

107
00:06:45,721 --> 00:06:48,321
We need you to come with us.

108
00:06:48,441 --> 00:06:50,081
Can I finish up first?

109
00:06:50,201 --> 00:06:51,641
Just draining the water slides.

110
00:06:51,761 --> 00:06:53,961
And the boating lakes.
And the rain forest floor.

111
00:06:55,481 --> 00:06:57,081
Plus, I'm waiting for my mates.

112
00:06:57,201 --> 00:06:59,201
Your friends
are inside the car.

113
00:06:59,321 --> 00:07:01,361
Worst Uber ever!

114
00:07:01,481 --> 00:07:03,241
Look, it's in
all your best interests

115
00:07:03,361 --> 00:07:04,481
that you come with us.

116
00:07:10,761 --> 00:07:12,401
SAT NAV: In half a mile,

117
00:07:12,521 --> 00:07:15,601
continue ahead
and merge with motorway.

118
00:07:25,721 --> 00:07:27,961
How are you doing?
Everything go all right?

119
00:07:31,241 --> 00:07:33,801
Apart from being kidnapped!

120
00:07:33,921 --> 00:07:36,721
Come on. What's the plan?

121
00:07:36,841 --> 00:07:39,081
I thought, let him take us
to where we're going.

122
00:07:39,201 --> 00:07:40,601
That way,
we find out who wants us.

123
00:07:40,721 --> 00:07:41,881
What if he kills us
along the way?

124
00:07:42,001 --> 00:07:42,921
Look at him.

125
00:07:43,041 --> 00:07:44,601
He's obviously doing this
at someone else's orders.

126
00:07:44,721 --> 00:07:46,401
Don't you want to know
who that is?

127
00:07:47,521 --> 00:07:49,521
SAT NAV: In 7100 yards...

128
00:07:49,641 --> 00:07:51,561
(AUDIO DISTORTS)

129
00:07:54,241 --> 00:07:56,041
Your equipment's
not up to much.

130
00:07:56,161 --> 00:07:57,561
It shouldn't be doing that.

131
00:08:01,441 --> 00:08:02,681
(GASPS)

132
00:08:04,281 --> 00:08:05,881
(TYRES SCREECH)

133
00:08:06,001 --> 00:08:08,521
(ALL SCREAM)

134
00:08:14,281 --> 00:08:16,121
(HORNS BLARE)

135
00:08:19,121 --> 00:08:20,601
We can't get out!

136
00:08:20,721 --> 00:08:23,161
- Yes, I got that, Yaz!
- Hey!

137
00:08:23,281 --> 00:08:25,241
Doc, the sat nav's
just started again!

138
00:08:25,361 --> 00:08:26,361
SAT NAV: In five seconds,

139
00:08:26,481 --> 00:08:28,361
- die.
- (BEEPING)

140
00:08:28,481 --> 00:08:31,241
SAT NAV: Die. Die.
Die. Die. Die...

141
00:08:31,361 --> 00:08:33,561
(AUDIO DISTORTS)
...Die. Die. Die...

142
00:08:35,041 --> 00:08:36,681
(TYRES SCREECH)

143
00:08:39,441 --> 00:08:41,241
The brake's not working!

144
00:08:41,361 --> 00:08:43,721
Someone's controlling this car,
and it isn't me!

145
00:08:48,161 --> 00:08:49,401
(SCREAMING)

146
00:08:52,961 --> 00:08:54,401
(SONIC BUZZES)

147
00:08:54,521 --> 00:08:56,681
There's got to be a way
to stop it!

148
00:08:56,801 --> 00:08:58,401
(SCREAMING)

149
00:09:05,161 --> 00:09:07,961
Look behind us! The road's out!
We're going over the edge!

150
00:09:08,081 --> 00:09:10,601
SAT NAV: ...Die. Die. Die...

151
00:09:10,721 --> 00:09:12,601
I need a reflective surface...

152
00:09:12,721 --> 00:09:14,721
SAT NAV: ...Die. Die. Die...

153
00:09:17,161 --> 00:09:19,641
- Hold on!
- (TYRES SCREECH)

154
00:09:29,521 --> 00:09:31,521
(ALL GASP)

155
00:09:33,201 --> 00:09:34,641
SPEAKER: What the hell
Just happened?

156
00:09:34,761 --> 00:09:36,841
What have you idiots
done with my car?

157
00:09:36,961 --> 00:09:38,121
Who's talking?

158
00:09:38,241 --> 00:09:40,201
Your car just assassinated
its driver

159
00:09:40,321 --> 00:09:41,881
and then attempted
to kill us!

160
00:09:42,001 --> 00:09:43,441
That's not possible.

161
00:09:43,561 --> 00:09:45,441
Tell me who you are,
and I'll tell you face to face

162
00:09:45,561 --> 00:09:46,881
just how possible
that actually was.

163
00:09:47,001 --> 00:09:50,321
This is C. I was having you
brought to London.

164
00:09:50,441 --> 00:09:52,121
To MI6.

165
00:09:55,041 --> 00:09:56,601
What? MI6 is trying to kill us?

166
00:09:56,721 --> 00:09:59,081
- No/
- Well, you nearly managed it.

167
00:09:59,201 --> 00:10:02,121
All right, C, you want us?
We want answers.

168
00:10:02,241 --> 00:10:04,561
We're coming in.

169
00:10:13,961 --> 00:10:15,841
Ah! At least they managed

170
00:10:15,961 --> 00:10:17,681
to transport my TARDIS
without damage.

171
00:10:19,161 --> 00:10:21,201
GRAHAM: Ryan, MI6!

172
00:10:21,321 --> 00:10:23,641
I always wanted to be a spy.

173
00:10:23,761 --> 00:10:26,201
- You'd be a rubbish spy.
- I'd be a great spy.

174
00:10:26,321 --> 00:10:28,201
- I'd just blend in.
- Well, well, well.

175
00:10:28,321 --> 00:10:29,881
Finally we meet.

176
00:10:30,001 --> 00:10:32,481
You actually do exist!

177
00:10:32,601 --> 00:10:35,321
- What?
- (WHISPERS)

178
00:10:35,441 --> 00:10:38,081
Don't be ridiculous, Franklin.
I've read the files.

179
00:10:38,201 --> 00:10:39,641
The Doctor is a man.

180
00:10:39,761 --> 00:10:41,121
I've had an upgrade.

181
00:10:41,241 --> 00:10:42,281
Hi.

182
00:10:42,401 --> 00:10:43,921
Oh...

183
00:10:44,041 --> 00:10:45,801
You just had us picked up
like criminals

184
00:10:45,921 --> 00:10:48,121
and put in a car
which tried to kill us.

185
00:10:48,241 --> 00:10:50,761
We were trying to bring
you here, not kill you,

186
00:10:50,881 --> 00:10:52,881
but our systems got hacked.

187
00:10:53,001 --> 00:10:55,681
Not exactly the best
demonstration of MI6 skills.

188
00:10:55,801 --> 00:10:57,081
I have been authorised

189
00:10:57,201 --> 00:10:59,961
to speak on behalf
of every security agency

190
00:11:00,081 --> 00:11:01,841
around the globe.

191
00:11:03,001 --> 00:11:04,481
We need your help...

192
00:11:04,601 --> 00:11:06,281
...Doctor.

193
00:11:08,481 --> 00:11:11,521
Over the past week,
there's been a spate of attacks

194
00:11:11,641 --> 00:11:13,761
on intelligence officers
worldwide,

195
00:11:13,881 --> 00:11:15,161
of every nationality.

196
00:11:15,281 --> 00:11:17,041
None of these attacks
has been ordered

197
00:11:17,161 --> 00:11:18,721
by rival intelligence agencies.

198
00:11:18,841 --> 00:11:20,601
At least that's what
you're all telling each other.

199
00:11:20,721 --> 00:11:22,521
No, we all have a very good
working knowledge

200
00:11:22,641 --> 00:11:23,841
of what our enemies are up to.

201
00:11:23,961 --> 00:11:26,241
No agency possesses
the technology

202
00:11:26,361 --> 00:11:28,521
to carry out
one of these attacks.

203
00:11:28,641 --> 00:11:31,081
None of us understands
how it was done.

204
00:11:31,201 --> 00:11:34,241
Or even what has been done.

205
00:11:34,361 --> 00:11:37,801
But every agent
has suffered the same fate.

206
00:11:46,721 --> 00:11:48,881
(MONITORS BEEP)

207
00:11:54,721 --> 00:11:56,881
She was found unconscious
on the floor

208
00:11:57,001 --> 00:11:59,721
of an aeroplane washroom
on a flight to Tokyo.

209
00:11:59,841 --> 00:12:02,641
She'd made pre-arranged contact
with an informant.

210
00:12:02,761 --> 00:12:04,481
Is she in a coma?

211
00:12:04,601 --> 00:12:08,481
Apparently, it's a little
more horrific than that.

212
00:12:09,601 --> 00:12:13,161
Now, I'm told
this is your expertise -

213
00:12:13,281 --> 00:12:16,121
dealing with the impossible.

214
00:12:17,801 --> 00:12:19,361
You're right.

215
00:12:19,481 --> 00:12:21,441
That is impossible.

216
00:12:21,561 --> 00:12:23,761
Her DNA's been rewritten.

217
00:12:23,881 --> 00:12:26,041
Every strand corrupted
and reshaped.

218
00:12:26,161 --> 00:12:27,721
She's no longer human.

219
00:12:27,841 --> 00:12:30,441
Just a shell
with a human appearance.

220
00:12:30,561 --> 00:12:32,121
Is she going to live, Doc?

221
00:12:32,241 --> 00:12:34,201
There's nothing of her fo live.

222
00:12:34,321 --> 00:12:36,521
It's like she's been erased.

223
00:12:36,641 --> 00:12:38,841
This is beyond
any human technology.

224
00:12:38,961 --> 00:12:40,321
Ah.

225
00:12:40,441 --> 00:12:43,201
I was rather worried
you were going to say that.

226
00:12:43,321 --> 00:12:47,801
Doctor, the security of
this entire planet is at stake.

227
00:12:47,921 --> 00:12:49,921
Can we rely upon you?

228
00:12:54,801 --> 00:12:57,521
C: Anaesthetic darts,
laser shoe gun,

229
00:12:57,641 --> 00:12:59,841
infrared ID duplicator,

230
00:12:59,961 --> 00:13:01,241
calendar hacker,

231
00:13:01,361 --> 00:13:03,161
lock-breakers,

232
00:13:03,281 --> 00:13:04,601
rocket-launcher cuff links,

233
00:13:04,721 --> 00:13:09,321
retinal ID decoder and
tongue-immobiliser chewing gum.

234
00:13:09,441 --> 00:13:10,841
How much more do you want?

235
00:13:10,961 --> 00:13:12,561
Yeah, it's great.
Keep 'em coming, C.

236
00:13:12,681 --> 00:13:15,481
- Yeah, bring on the bling.
- They are not toys!

237
00:13:15,601 --> 00:13:17,121
Yeah. They're not toys, Graham.

238
00:13:17,241 --> 00:13:18,441
No, they're not, Ryan,

239
00:13:18,561 --> 00:13:21,201
and if you say otherwise,
I will shoot you

240
00:13:21,321 --> 00:13:23,121
with my laser shoe!

241
00:13:23,241 --> 00:13:26,481
C: All of the assassinated
agents were investigating

242
00:13:26,601 --> 00:13:28,841
leads relating to this man.

243
00:13:30,321 --> 00:13:32,481
Daniel Barton.
Born in Bromsgrove.

244
00:13:32,601 --> 00:13:34,361
Now lives
just north of San Francisco.

245
00:13:34,481 --> 00:13:37,281
- He's the founder of VOR.
- The search engine.

246
00:13:37,401 --> 00:13:41,121
Web, apps, social,
global mapping, advertising,

247
00:13:41,241 --> 00:13:43,321
scientific
and medical research,

248
00:13:43,441 --> 00:13:44,801
robotics, data polling,

249
00:13:44,921 --> 00:13:46,321
human analytics...

250
00:13:46,441 --> 00:13:50,161
Right now, VOR is more powerful
than most nations.

251
00:13:50,281 --> 00:13:52,121
Daniel Barton is the man

252
00:13:52,241 --> 00:13:54,481
who built it all up
from the ground.

253
00:13:54,601 --> 00:13:56,361
We're going to need
your best man on this.

254
00:13:56,481 --> 00:13:58,241
What do you call him?
Horizon-watcher?

255
00:13:58,361 --> 00:13:59,681
Oh.

256
00:13:59,801 --> 00:14:02,401
- Exactly.
- Well, he...um...

257
00:14:02,521 --> 00:14:04,121
He left.

258
00:14:04,241 --> 00:14:05,921
I...sacked him.

259
00:14:06,041 --> 00:14:07,881
The only person with
an open mind about all this

260
00:14:08,001 --> 00:14:08,921
and you let him go?

261
00:14:09,041 --> 00:14:11,721
MI6 has never countenanced

262
00:14:11,841 --> 00:14:14,281
the possibility
of extraterrestrial life.

263
00:14:14,401 --> 00:14:17,001
Well, you should talk
to your mates at GCHQ!

264
00:14:17,121 --> 00:14:19,121
The country
has other organisations

265
00:14:19,241 --> 00:14:20,561
that deal with all that!

266
00:14:20,681 --> 00:14:22,561
UNIT. Even Torchwood.

267
00:14:22,681 --> 00:14:24,121
They're all gone.

268
00:14:24,241 --> 00:14:26,721
Oh, C! You took your eye
off the horizon

269
00:14:26,841 --> 00:14:28,641
just as things
were coming over it.

270
00:14:28,761 --> 00:14:30,201
Don't worry. I'll call him.

271
00:14:30,321 --> 00:14:32,401
You can't. He's off-grid.

272
00:14:32,521 --> 00:14:35,121
We can't find him anywhere.
Believe me, we've tried.

273
00:14:35,241 --> 00:14:36,401
Shh. I'm WhatsApping.

274
00:14:36,521 --> 00:14:37,521
Hi. It's me.

275
00:14:37,641 --> 00:14:40,641
I'm at MI6 with C. Crisis.

276
00:14:40,761 --> 00:14:42,081
Big crisis.

277
00:14:42,201 --> 00:14:43,481
Serious crisis.

278
00:14:43,601 --> 00:14:46,001
Big, serious crisis.

279
00:14:46,121 --> 00:14:49,401
And C says you were right and
he's sorry for being an idiot.

280
00:14:49,521 --> 00:14:50,921
I did not use those words!

281
00:14:51,041 --> 00:14:53,081
Send us your location. Kisses.

282
00:14:53,201 --> 00:14:55,081
It's quite French, that,
isn't it?

283
00:14:55,201 --> 00:14:56,521
- Kisses?
- (PHONE PINGS)

284
00:14:56,641 --> 00:14:57,561
Ah!

285
00:14:57,681 --> 00:14:59,401
- See?
- G Yes?

286
00:15:00,801 --> 00:15:02,081
- It's a fish.
- I know!

287
00:15:02,201 --> 00:15:04,521
C: Can we please focus?
Daniel Barton

288
00:15:04,641 --> 00:15:06,641
isn't just
a powerful businessman.

289
00:15:06,761 --> 00:15:08,161
He was also one of our agents

290
00:15:08,281 --> 00:15:10,281
when he first went
to work in the US.

291
00:15:10,401 --> 00:15:12,521
Then he withdrew cooperation.

292
00:15:13,681 --> 00:15:15,481
It's possible
he became a double agent.

293
00:15:15,601 --> 00:15:18,001
- Or even a triple.
- Who for?

294
00:15:18,121 --> 00:15:20,121
- (GLASS SHATTERS)

295
00:15:20,241 --> 00:15:22,121
(GASPS)

296
00:15:23,841 --> 00:15:25,961
- Down!
- (ALL GASP)

297
00:15:26,081 --> 00:15:27,641
Go!

298
00:15:27,761 --> 00:15:29,121
(GROANS)

299
00:15:31,841 --> 00:15:33,161
Get to the TARDIS!

300
00:15:42,761 --> 00:15:44,441
Agh!

301
00:15:50,481 --> 00:15:52,641
DOCTOR: We've got
to get out of here.

302
00:15:52,761 --> 00:15:54,001
GRAHAM: We've still got
the gadgets.

303
00:15:54,121 --> 00:15:57,161
We just saw the head of MI6
get assassinated.

304
00:15:57,281 --> 00:15:59,361
Yeah, by the same sort of bolts
that came through that sat nav.

305
00:15:59,481 --> 00:16:00,921
Where's that picture?
I need to set the coordinates.

306
00:16:01,041 --> 00:16:02,761
Ooh, I've got it.

307
00:16:02,881 --> 00:16:06,121
So, wrong place, wrong time
twice in one day.

308
00:16:06,241 --> 00:16:07,761
That's got to make us targets.

309
00:16:07,881 --> 00:16:10,721
And why do you keep looking
at pictures of a fish?

310
00:16:10,841 --> 00:16:12,921
Steganography.
There's another image

311
00:16:13,041 --> 00:16:15,161
hidden within the pixels
of that photo.

312
00:16:15,281 --> 00:16:16,721
It's basic spy craft
in your time.

313
00:16:16,841 --> 00:16:17,841
Easy way to smuggle out
information

314
00:16:17,961 --> 00:16:20,081
because there's
no pattern to look for.

315
00:16:20,201 --> 00:16:22,001
- (CRACKING)
- No two stegs are the same.

316
00:16:22,121 --> 00:16:23,241
RYAN: So one's hidden
inside the other?

317
00:16:23,361 --> 00:16:24,361
- Doc.
- Exactly.

318
00:16:24,481 --> 00:16:26,801
Luckily, I can read pixels.
I took a correspondence class.

319
00:16:26,921 --> 00:16:29,121
- Doc...
- Ooh, the outback.

320
00:16:29,241 --> 00:16:30,321
Gone full hermit.

321
00:16:30,441 --> 00:16:32,681
Doctor,
something's trying to get in!

322
00:16:32,801 --> 00:16:34,521
(CRACKING)

323
00:16:34,641 --> 00:16:36,001
Oh, no, you don't.

324
00:16:41,801 --> 00:16:45,001
(TARDIS THRUMS)

325
00:16:47,001 --> 00:16:48,601
(SONIC BUZZES)

326
00:16:50,281 --> 00:16:51,761
(BUZZING AND THRUMMING STOP)

327
00:16:51,881 --> 00:16:54,441
I didn't know things could get
into the TARDIS like that.

328
00:16:54,561 --> 00:16:56,281
Neither did 1.

329
00:16:57,361 --> 00:16:58,641
RYAN: But you got rid of it.

330
00:16:58,761 --> 00:17:00,241
GRAHAM: Yeah, but what was it?

331
00:17:00,361 --> 00:17:04,201
At a guess, the same thing
that attacked all those spies.

332
00:17:04,321 --> 00:17:06,481
- And possibly us.
- (SONIC BLOOPS)

333
00:17:06,601 --> 00:17:07,841
What?

334
00:17:07,961 --> 00:17:09,921
No readings?

335
00:17:10,041 --> 00:17:11,961
The sonic can usually
read everything.

336
00:17:12,081 --> 00:17:13,801
All right, park that.

337
00:17:13,921 --> 00:17:17,761
Live attacks. They're after us,
but we need intel.

338
00:17:19,121 --> 00:17:22,441
Split resources. Graham,
me and you are off to Australia

339
00:17:22,561 --> 00:17:24,441
to see my old mate
from MI6. I say old mate -

340
00:17:24,561 --> 00:17:26,321
I've met him once,
but he seemed very nice.

341
00:17:26,441 --> 00:17:27,601
We text, though.
Does that count?

342
00:17:27,721 --> 00:17:29,001
- If you say so.
- Yaz, Ryan,

343
00:17:29,121 --> 00:17:30,841
how do you feel
about undercover work?

344
00:17:30,961 --> 00:17:32,161
- Definitely!
- I don't know.

345
00:17:32,281 --> 00:17:35,801
Daniel Barton -
he's our best lead.

346
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:37,961
Well, he's our only lead.

347
00:17:38,081 --> 00:17:41,241
We'll get you a cover story.
Hack his diary, get in there,

348
00:17:41,361 --> 00:17:43,521
check him out. Infiltrate VOR.
Have a nose

349
00:17:43,641 --> 00:17:45,881
- around their systems.
- Be spies, basically.

350
00:17:47,041 --> 00:17:49,601
GRAHAM: What,
with absolutely no training?

351
00:17:49,721 --> 00:17:52,281
- We got the gadgets.
- All the gear, but no idea.

352
00:17:52,401 --> 00:17:54,921
- Oh, thanks a lot.
- No, I think you'll be great.

353
00:17:55,041 --> 00:17:56,681
I have total confidence,
you know?

354
00:17:56,801 --> 00:17:58,041
Just, um...

355
00:17:58,161 --> 00:18:00,241
Just be careful, though.

356
00:18:00,361 --> 00:18:01,801
It's safe for them, though,
right?

357
00:18:01,921 --> 00:18:03,321
Yeah. 80% sure.

358
00:18:03,441 --> 00:18:04,441
75.

359
00:18:04,561 --> 00:18:06,281
40% - absolute minimum.

360
00:18:06,401 --> 00:18:08,201
Take this.

361
00:18:08,321 --> 00:18:11,081
Bio-scanner disguised
as a digital recorder.

362
00:18:11,201 --> 00:18:13,081
I want to know everything
about Daniel Barton.

363
00:18:13,201 --> 00:18:15,121
Like Graham said, be careful.

364
00:18:15,241 --> 00:18:16,681
Stay in touch.

365
00:18:16,801 --> 00:18:19,401
And remember,
rule 1 of espionage -

366
00:18:19,521 --> 00:18:21,721
trust no-one.

367
00:18:28,641 --> 00:18:30,201
Diary hacked, got us in.

368
00:18:30,321 --> 00:18:31,601
Loving these toys.

369
00:18:31,721 --> 00:18:33,721
- Which building is it?
- That one there.

370
00:18:33,841 --> 00:18:34,841
Though according to the files,

371
00:18:34,961 --> 00:18:36,401
this whole development
is down to Barton.

372
00:18:36,521 --> 00:18:39,841
So, you journalist,
me photographer?

373
00:18:39,961 --> 00:18:41,921
Yeah. That works, doesn't it?

374
00:18:42,041 --> 00:18:43,241
I reckon.

375
00:18:43,361 --> 00:18:45,481
We've just got to try and be
confident with it, haven't we?

376
00:18:45,601 --> 00:18:47,441
Try not to panic that
we're blagging our way in

377
00:18:47,561 --> 00:18:49,001
on someone
who might be dangerous.

378
00:18:49,121 --> 00:18:51,281
And don't obsess on
our total lack of spy training.

379
00:18:51,401 --> 00:18:52,801
Yeah. Don't obsess on that.

380
00:18:52,921 --> 00:18:54,601
Think how
the Doctor would do it.

381
00:18:54,721 --> 00:18:56,121
Swan in there
like she owns the place,

382
00:18:56,241 --> 00:18:58,241
big smiles, loads of chat,
total confidence.

383
00:18:58,361 --> 00:19:00,161
We can do this.

384
00:19:01,241 --> 00:19:02,361
Why are you looking so worried?

385
00:19:02,481 --> 00:19:05,761
I decided my spy name would be
Logan, and now I'm worried

386
00:19:05,881 --> 00:19:07,801
I don't look anything
like Hugh Jackman.

387
00:19:07,921 --> 00:19:09,521
Ryan, you're panicking.

388
00:19:09,641 --> 00:19:10,841
Rule 1 - no panicking.

389
00:19:10,961 --> 00:19:12,801
I thought rule I was
don't trust anybody!

390
00:19:12,921 --> 00:19:14,041
Rule 13, then - no panicking

391
00:19:14,161 --> 00:19:15,761
while you're not
trusting anyone!

392
00:19:19,441 --> 00:19:21,721
I am so sorry about
the diary snafu, sir.

393
00:19:21,841 --> 00:19:23,521
Oh, dear, this must be them.

394
00:19:23,641 --> 00:19:26,601
Hi! I'm sure
you recognise Mr Barton.

395
00:19:26,721 --> 00:19:28,041
RYAN: Certainly do.

396
00:19:28,161 --> 00:19:29,601
- This is Sofia Afzal.
- Hi.

397
00:19:29,721 --> 00:19:32,161
- And this is Logan...?
- I'm Logan.

398
00:19:32,281 --> 00:19:34,521
The name's Logan Jackson.
I'm the photographer.

399
00:19:34,641 --> 00:19:35,961
I'm Sofia. He's nervous.

400
00:19:36,081 --> 00:19:37,481
Big fan of yours.

401
00:19:37,601 --> 00:19:39,641
(GIGGLES) I'm not nervous.
Who's nervous?

402
00:19:39,761 --> 00:19:40,801
Hi.

403
00:19:40,921 --> 00:19:42,481
Logan. I'm... I'm Logan.

404
00:19:42,601 --> 00:19:43,801
Daniel.

405
00:19:43,921 --> 00:19:45,801
Don't be nervous. I don't bite.

406
00:19:45,921 --> 00:19:49,321
Only my own staff.
Especially after this mix-up.

407
00:19:49,441 --> 00:19:51,201
I had to fire half the PR team.

408
00:19:51,321 --> 00:19:53,321
- You haven't?
- No, not half.

409
00:19:54,481 --> 00:19:56,601
Uh... He's kidding. Just...two.

410
00:19:56,721 --> 00:19:58,561
Shall we go up?

411
00:20:01,921 --> 00:20:04,721
I'm sure they'll be able
to find other jobs. Won't they?

412
00:20:11,521 --> 00:20:14,201
(TARDIS THRUMS)

413
00:20:22,961 --> 00:20:24,281
Worth racing up from the city

414
00:20:24,401 --> 00:20:27,041
- just for that.
- Got to be a trick, right?

415
00:20:27,161 --> 00:20:28,601
Projection? Mirrors?

416
00:20:30,041 --> 00:20:31,841
Say hello to the Doctor.

417
00:20:33,201 --> 00:20:35,241
I see you decoded the fish.

418
00:20:35,361 --> 00:20:37,561
- Fancy a cuppa?
- Very much.

419
00:20:37,681 --> 00:20:39,721
Hello.
This is my friend Graham.

420
00:20:39,841 --> 00:20:40,561
O!

421
00:20:40,681 --> 00:20:43,001
- Sorry, you're...?
- 0.

422
00:20:43,121 --> 00:20:44,601
- 07
- 0.

423
00:20:44,721 --> 00:20:46,721
- Oh.
- It was a joke

424
00:20:46,841 --> 00:20:48,121
by the others at MI6.

425
00:20:48,241 --> 00:20:50,201
Whenever I came into the room
to meet C,

426
00:20:50,321 --> 00:20:52,121
he'd go, "Oh, God!"

427
00:20:52,241 --> 00:20:53,241
Oh!

428
00:20:53,361 --> 00:20:56,761
It sort of stuck,
and now I've owned it.

429
00:20:56,881 --> 00:20:59,721
This is Seesay and Browning.

430
00:20:59,841 --> 00:21:01,201
Just arrived.

431
00:21:01,321 --> 00:21:03,281
Australian secret service.

432
00:21:03,401 --> 00:21:04,841
We'll be out here
for the whole of your visit.

433
00:21:04,961 --> 00:21:06,361
We're under orders
to keep all of you safe.

434
00:21:06,481 --> 00:21:08,041
Safe from what?

435
00:21:08,161 --> 00:21:09,321
Not sure.

436
00:21:09,441 --> 00:21:11,201
You're going to be a right lot
of help, then, aren't you?

437
00:21:12,721 --> 00:21:14,041
Can I take a nose
around your gaff?

438
00:21:14,161 --> 00:21:16,041
I love the outback.

439
00:21:16,161 --> 00:21:18,521
I once lived in the outback
for 123 years.

440
00:21:18,641 --> 00:21:20,921
I saw some great rocks.

441
00:21:25,441 --> 00:21:26,761
Cosy!

442
00:21:26,881 --> 00:21:28,401
You mean messy.

443
00:21:28,521 --> 00:21:30,401
You're right, I do.

444
00:21:30,521 --> 00:21:33,161
Didn't realise you were
this much of a hoarder.

445
00:21:34,241 --> 00:21:35,881
What is all this stuff?

446
00:21:36,001 --> 00:21:38,961
The full MI6 record
of the unexplained.

447
00:21:39,081 --> 00:21:41,001
As compiled by me.

448
00:21:41,121 --> 00:21:44,441
Human disappearances, sightings
of unidentified objects,

449
00:21:44,561 --> 00:21:47,081
mysterious beings,
possible alien incursions

450
00:21:47,201 --> 00:21:48,201
going back centuries.

451
00:21:48,321 --> 00:21:52,281
And a complete set of Fortean
Times in mint condition.

452
00:21:56,041 --> 00:21:58,081
Look at all the evidence
I gathered.

453
00:21:58,201 --> 00:22:00,361
And they just mocked me.

454
00:22:00,481 --> 00:22:02,121
No-one's mocking you now.

455
00:22:03,921 --> 00:22:06,121
I heard C was shot.

456
00:22:06,241 --> 00:22:07,401
We were there.

457
00:22:07,521 --> 00:22:08,921
Nearly got us an' all.

458
00:22:11,921 --> 00:22:14,681
Does this connect
to the attacks on agents?

459
00:22:15,721 --> 00:22:18,041
I have been monitoring
the chatter, Doctor.

460
00:22:19,641 --> 00:22:21,161
Is it aliens?

461
00:22:21,281 --> 00:22:24,881
Aliens attacking spies
all over the world?

462
00:22:25,001 --> 00:22:26,761
And rewriting their DNA.

463
00:22:26,881 --> 00:22:28,801
That's terrifying. But...

464
00:22:28,921 --> 00:22:31,001
- Wow! Why would they do that?
- I don't know.

465
00:22:31,121 --> 00:22:33,201
They almost infiltrated my
TARDIS as we were taking off.

466
00:22:33,321 --> 00:22:34,881
I thought you might
have something

467
00:22:35,001 --> 00:22:38,081
in your research banks
that might give us some clues.

468
00:22:38,201 --> 00:22:41,681
Wow! This is some setup.
Paranoid, are we?

469
00:22:41,801 --> 00:22:43,361
No. I prefer cautious.

470
00:22:43,481 --> 00:22:45,241
I like to know
if anything's watching me.

471
00:22:46,681 --> 00:22:49,081
And if you're already
in the middle of all of this,

472
00:22:49,201 --> 00:22:51,001
how do you know
they won't follow you here?

473
00:22:52,081 --> 00:22:53,961
How do you know
you haven't become targets too?

474
00:22:54,081 --> 00:22:56,721
I have to be honest
with you - you only got in

475
00:22:56,841 --> 00:22:58,281
cos you're Brits.

476
00:22:58,401 --> 00:23:00,081
And my mum reads your paper.

477
00:23:00,201 --> 00:23:01,441
She's old.

478
00:23:01,561 --> 00:23:04,121
Still into legacy media.

479
00:23:04,241 --> 00:23:05,561
We know you're busy,

480
00:23:05,681 --> 00:23:07,721
so Logan will take a few photos
while we chat.

481
00:23:09,681 --> 00:23:10,721
OK if I record?

482
00:23:14,721 --> 00:23:17,241
- (BEEPS)
- Right, then.

483
00:23:17,361 --> 00:23:18,321
Good to go?

484
00:23:18,441 --> 00:23:20,761
Just searching you up.

485
00:23:20,881 --> 00:23:22,641
Check you are
who you say you are.

486
00:23:30,961 --> 00:23:32,961
Fire away, then.

487
00:23:36,601 --> 00:23:38,241
Boy from Bromsgrove.

488
00:23:38,361 --> 00:23:40,521
Council estate,
local comprehensive.

489
00:23:40,641 --> 00:23:44,041
Now with his own collection
of planes and motorbikes.

490
00:23:45,241 --> 00:23:46,641
And a private airport.

491
00:23:46,761 --> 00:23:48,881
We couldn't afford to go abroad
when I was a kid.

492
00:23:49,001 --> 00:23:51,201
Now flying's
one of my big hobbies.

493
00:23:51,321 --> 00:23:53,041
I've even got
my own passenger plane.

494
00:23:53,161 --> 00:23:55,481
I fly my mates around the world

495
00:23:55,601 --> 00:23:58,561
and insult them over
the intercom during the flight.

496
00:23:58,681 --> 00:23:59,601
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

497
00:23:59,721 --> 00:24:02,361
I bet that goes down well. So,
how did you end up here, then?

498
00:24:02,481 --> 00:24:05,761
A combination of inspiring
computer science teacher,

499
00:24:05,881 --> 00:24:09,361
plus being one of the few
non-white faces at my school.

500
00:24:09,481 --> 00:24:12,241
I spent a lot of time
in my bedroom with my computer.

501
00:24:12,361 --> 00:24:14,241
I started small,
just trying to build

502
00:24:14,361 --> 00:24:15,281
a knowledge base.

503
00:24:15,401 --> 00:24:16,761
Trying to connect people
with data.

504
00:24:16,881 --> 00:24:20,041
And that became the biggest
search engine on the planet.

505
00:24:20,161 --> 00:24:22,041
And more.
This company is far more

506
00:24:22,161 --> 00:24:23,841
than just a search engine now.

507
00:24:23,961 --> 00:24:25,841
Sure.
But the same principles apply.

508
00:24:25,961 --> 00:24:28,201
The more data we share,
the better it is for the world.

509
00:24:29,681 --> 00:24:31,521
Unless you count
disinformation.

510
00:24:31,641 --> 00:24:33,721
Online abuse. Cyber bullying.

511
00:24:33,841 --> 00:24:35,681
All of which you've been
accused of ignoring.

512
00:24:35,801 --> 00:24:37,401
Haven't you?

513
00:24:37,521 --> 00:24:41,161
Well, we have three start-ups
currently trying to figure out

514
00:24:41,281 --> 00:24:42,761
how to combat them.

515
00:24:42,881 --> 00:24:45,001
We did something great,
and it got hijacked.

516
00:24:45,121 --> 00:24:48,281
I get to see both sides
of humanity in this job.

517
00:24:48,401 --> 00:24:51,521
And do you know what, Sofia?
It turns out

518
00:24:51,641 --> 00:24:53,921
you can't entirely
trust everyone.

519
00:24:57,721 --> 00:24:58,761
(PHONE VIBRATES)

520
00:24:58,881 --> 00:25:02,401
Sorry.
I've got to cut this short.

521
00:25:02,521 --> 00:25:06,281
- Something needs my attention.
- We were just getting started.

522
00:25:07,481 --> 00:25:08,721
You want to know who I am?

523
00:25:08,841 --> 00:25:11,281
You want to see my house,
meet my friends?

524
00:25:11,401 --> 00:25:13,201
Cos it's my birthday tomorrow.

525
00:25:13,321 --> 00:25:14,681
I'm having a party.

526
00:25:14,801 --> 00:25:17,921
Everyone who knows me
will be there. Come along -

527
00:25:18,041 --> 00:25:20,121
as my apology
for running out on you.

528
00:25:22,761 --> 00:25:26,121
I've managed
to duplicate his access pass.

529
00:25:26,241 --> 00:25:28,561
If we find a place to hide
and do some snooping around

530
00:25:28,681 --> 00:25:29,881
whilst everyone knocks off...

531
00:25:30,001 --> 00:25:32,641
Hey!
Why are you looking all weird?

532
00:25:32,761 --> 00:25:34,321
DNA profile.

533
00:25:34,441 --> 00:25:36,721
Only 93% human.

534
00:25:36,841 --> 00:25:38,401
What's the other 7%?

535
00:25:39,681 --> 00:25:41,481
Who is this guy?

536
00:25:43,921 --> 00:25:47,921
This place - it's open and flat
and empty the whole way round.

537
00:25:50,441 --> 00:25:51,481
So why does it feel like

538
00:25:51,601 --> 00:25:53,321
there are things
moving out there?

539
00:25:59,521 --> 00:26:01,841
(WHIRRING AND BEEPING)

540
00:26:01,961 --> 00:26:03,361
GRAHAM: What just happened?

541
00:26:03,481 --> 00:26:06,321
Two movement sensors tripped.

542
00:26:19,001 --> 00:26:20,561
(SECURITY LIGHT TRIPS)

543
00:26:25,001 --> 00:26:26,401
What's doing that?

544
00:26:27,761 --> 00:26:30,601
What have you brought here,
Doctor?

545
00:26:32,161 --> 00:26:33,681
I don't know.

546
00:26:33,801 --> 00:26:36,521
Let's take a look outside.

547
00:26:36,641 --> 00:26:39,961
Looking outside was actually
quite low on my list.

548
00:26:40,081 --> 00:26:42,641
But when does she
ever listen to me?

549
00:26:44,841 --> 00:26:46,041
(ANIMAL HOWLS)

550
00:26:46,161 --> 00:26:47,601
(DOOR CLATTERS)

551
00:26:47,721 --> 00:26:49,961
Please, all of you,
back inside!

552
00:26:50,081 --> 00:26:51,681
(SONIC BUZZES)

553
00:26:53,961 --> 00:26:55,321
No readings.

554
00:26:55,441 --> 00:26:56,361
You didn't get any readings

555
00:26:56,481 --> 00:26:57,761
off that thing
in the TARDIS either.

556
00:26:57,881 --> 00:27:00,281
Exactly. There's something...

557
00:27:01,601 --> 00:27:04,041
It's like I can sense them.

558
00:27:04,161 --> 00:27:06,201
- I know what you mean.
- They're out there, hiding.

559
00:27:06,321 --> 00:27:09,481
Tripping the sensors to let us
know that they're here.

560
00:27:09,601 --> 00:27:10,921
It's like they're watching us.

561
00:27:11,041 --> 00:27:13,761
Like animals
stalking their prey.

562
00:27:16,441 --> 00:27:18,081
Sorry, that wasn't helpful.

563
00:27:18,201 --> 00:27:20,121
From what I understand, we were
sent here cos you're one

564
00:27:20,241 --> 00:27:22,401
of the few people that can stop
the attacks on our colleagues.

565
00:27:22,521 --> 00:27:23,841
So, please, go inside,

566
00:27:23,961 --> 00:27:26,081
figure it out, and let us
do the job we came for.

567
00:27:26,201 --> 00:27:29,001
Doc... Come on.

568
00:27:32,961 --> 00:27:35,441
SEESAY: I'll take round
the back. Stay on comms.

569
00:27:36,561 --> 00:27:38,961
OVER RADIO:
Circling around eastwards.

570
00:27:39,081 --> 00:27:40,561
Understood.

571
00:27:46,121 --> 00:27:48,161
(LIGHT CLICKS OFF)

572
00:27:56,761 --> 00:27:58,641
(LIGHT CLICKS ON)

573
00:27:58,761 --> 00:28:01,481
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

574
00:28:04,921 --> 00:28:06,481
SEESAY: See those lights
going on and off?

575
00:28:06,601 --> 00:28:09,561
BROWNING: It's where I am,
but it's not me.

576
00:28:40,361 --> 00:28:42,681
(BROWNING GASPS)

577
00:28:44,321 --> 00:28:45,561
Browning!

578
00:28:46,801 --> 00:28:48,081
Stay back!

579
00:28:49,281 --> 00:28:50,561
Run!

580
00:28:50,681 --> 00:28:52,921
Oh, my God!

581
00:28:53,041 --> 00:28:54,201
What are they?

582
00:29:01,361 --> 00:29:03,081
Get away from them!

583
00:29:03,201 --> 00:29:05,841
(ROARING)

584
00:29:09,681 --> 00:29:12,041
We can't fight them out here,
Doctor.

585
00:29:13,281 --> 00:29:15,081
Strategic retreat.

586
00:29:16,321 --> 00:29:17,881
Fine.

587
00:29:22,881 --> 00:29:24,321
No signals off any of them.

588
00:29:24,441 --> 00:29:27,921
They've just obliterated
those bodies. What can they be?

589
00:29:28,041 --> 00:29:29,561
(BEEPING)

590
00:29:29,681 --> 00:29:30,761
Looks like they're moving.

591
00:29:30,881 --> 00:29:32,281
They're surrounding
the building, look.

592
00:29:32,401 --> 00:29:34,161
- That's what we want?
- Do we?

593
00:29:34,281 --> 00:29:35,561
Yeah.

594
00:29:35,681 --> 00:29:37,961
Just a little closer...

595
00:29:40,201 --> 00:29:41,921
(GASPS)

596
00:29:50,241 --> 00:29:52,521
- Did you kill 'em?
- More like they retreated.

597
00:29:52,641 --> 00:29:55,841
- How did you know that'd work?
- I didn't. Gambled.

598
00:29:55,961 --> 00:29:57,161
Some kit you've got here.

599
00:29:57,281 --> 00:29:59,241
I've had a few years
to rig it out.

600
00:29:59,361 --> 00:30:01,121
- Just in case.
- No, no, look.

601
00:30:01,241 --> 00:30:02,681
There's one still outside.

602
00:30:09,241 --> 00:30:11,281
Plan B. I've got a plan B.

603
00:30:11,401 --> 00:30:14,041
It's in the blueprints, Doctor,
just under the folder.

604
00:30:14,161 --> 00:30:15,721
I rigged it
in case anything got past

605
00:30:15,841 --> 00:30:17,361
the first line of defence.

606
00:30:20,801 --> 00:30:23,881
GRAHAM: It's coming through
the wall! How can it do that?

607
00:30:24,001 --> 00:30:26,201
DOCTOR: Physical boundaries
don't stop it.

608
00:30:26,321 --> 00:30:27,681
It's still not used
to this planet

609
00:30:27,801 --> 00:30:29,001
or maybe even this reality.

610
00:30:37,841 --> 00:30:39,721
- Spring-loaded?
- Yep.

611
00:30:39,841 --> 00:30:40,961
What are you talking about?

612
00:30:45,641 --> 00:30:48,041
Oh, you could have warned me
about that!

613
00:30:48,161 --> 00:30:50,641
Re-route the charge.
We've got to keep it in there.

614
00:30:50,761 --> 00:30:53,001
- A bit quicker!
- Yes! Doing my best.

615
00:30:55,201 --> 00:30:56,241
That thing can't hold it.

616
00:30:56,361 --> 00:30:57,961
Is he just here for
the running commentary?

617
00:30:59,641 --> 00:31:01,601
(SCREECHES)

618
00:31:06,321 --> 00:31:09,001
It worked! It actually worked!

619
00:31:10,681 --> 00:31:12,481
(SPARKING AND FIZZING)

620
00:31:22,481 --> 00:31:23,601
Who are you?

621
00:31:27,201 --> 00:31:29,401
What are you doing
to the people on this planet?

622
00:31:31,281 --> 00:31:33,241
Why are you changing their DNA?

623
00:31:35,321 --> 00:31:38,401
And why spies? Why are you
only attacking spies?

624
00:31:39,481 --> 00:31:42,441
What are you, exactly,
except for reluctant to talk?

625
00:31:43,561 --> 00:31:45,561
I'm thinking one more blast.

626
00:31:47,001 --> 00:31:48,441
How many are you

627
00:31:48,561 --> 00:31:51,921
in your race or species
or whatever you are?

628
00:31:54,881 --> 00:31:56,841
Where are you from?

629
00:31:58,481 --> 00:32:00,321
CREATURE: Far beyond.

630
00:32:02,801 --> 00:32:06,281
So you can communicate, then.
Beyond where?

631
00:32:06,401 --> 00:32:10,481
CREATURE: Your understanding!
(CHUCKLES)

632
00:32:10,601 --> 00:32:11,841
I think it's laughing
at you, Doc.

633
00:32:11,961 --> 00:32:13,761
Yes, I got that!

634
00:32:13,881 --> 00:32:16,041
Is this your native form,

635
00:32:16,161 --> 00:32:18,161
wherever it is you're from?

636
00:32:18,281 --> 00:32:20,721
Is this what you look like
at home?

637
00:32:20,841 --> 00:32:23,561
CREATURE:
We take this form to mock you.

638
00:32:26,281 --> 00:32:29,001
Your shape amuses us.

639
00:32:29,121 --> 00:32:30,361
Very funny.

640
00:32:30,481 --> 00:32:33,681
CREATURE: We are stable now.
We are ready.

641
00:32:33,801 --> 00:32:35,561
What does that mean, "stable"?

642
00:32:35,681 --> 00:32:37,361
Ready for what?

643
00:32:37,481 --> 00:32:40,641
- CREATURE: To take this.
- To take this what? Hut?

644
00:32:40,761 --> 00:32:42,601
Country? Planet?

645
00:32:44,921 --> 00:32:46,601
CREATURE: Universe.

646
00:32:54,201 --> 00:32:55,681
RYAN: Data from Barton's pass
says

647
00:32:55,801 --> 00:32:57,001
he left the building hours ago.

648
00:32:57,121 --> 00:32:58,961
Everyone must have gone by now.

649
00:32:59,081 --> 00:33:00,761
Let's have a look.

650
00:33:11,761 --> 00:33:13,521
(BEEP)

651
00:33:16,281 --> 00:33:18,161
- (BEEP)
- RYAN: We're in.

652
00:33:21,841 --> 00:33:24,961
YAZ: Right.
We've got to be quick.

653
00:33:25,081 --> 00:33:26,201
If the Doctor's right,

654
00:33:26,321 --> 00:33:28,321
that should download
every piece of data

655
00:33:28,441 --> 00:33:30,121
his computer has ever
had access to.

656
00:33:32,441 --> 00:33:34,121
- Have you seen this?
- RYAN: What? That thing

657
00:33:34,241 --> 00:33:36,441
in the case over there?
Yeah, a bit creepy.

658
00:33:36,561 --> 00:33:38,641
YAZ: No. All these cameras.

659
00:33:40,921 --> 00:33:42,801
He's got screens
monitoring half the building.

660
00:33:42,921 --> 00:33:44,441
Control freak, innit?

661
00:33:44,561 --> 00:33:46,561
How long do you reckon
the thing's going to take?

662
00:33:46,681 --> 00:33:48,881
Let's see.

663
00:33:57,281 --> 00:33:59,281
YAZ: Still clear?

664
00:33:59,401 --> 00:34:01,281
RYAN: Yep, all good.

665
00:34:02,601 --> 00:34:04,161
YAZ: You know my sister's
still proper cross

666
00:34:04,281 --> 00:34:05,801
I haven't given her
your phone number.

667
00:34:05,921 --> 00:34:07,961
- Why haven't you?
- Ryan, you're my mate.

668
00:34:08,081 --> 00:34:09,681
I don't want you
snogging my sister!

669
00:34:09,801 --> 00:34:11,161
She's all right, your sister.

670
00:34:11,281 --> 00:34:13,681
- Can you not, please?
- Just give me her number, Yaz.

671
00:34:13,801 --> 00:34:14,601
Shut up!

672
00:34:14,721 --> 00:34:18,201
I could be your brother-in-law.
I'd be a good brother-in-law.

673
00:34:19,761 --> 00:34:20,961
(BEEPING)

674
00:34:21,081 --> 00:34:22,961
Barton's back in the building.

675
00:34:23,081 --> 00:34:26,561
His pass just got access.
He's coming this way!

676
00:34:27,481 --> 00:34:29,081
I'm not done! How close is he?

677
00:34:30,761 --> 00:34:32,801
Quick, Yaz! He's coming!

678
00:34:32,921 --> 00:34:34,521
Get off the computer!

679
00:34:39,241 --> 00:34:41,361
Bag, bag, bag...

680
00:34:41,481 --> 00:34:43,281
There it is.

681
00:34:52,841 --> 00:34:54,801
I know you're here.

682
00:34:56,481 --> 00:34:58,161
Show yourselves.

683
00:34:59,441 --> 00:35:02,201
(FIZZING AND CRACKING)

684
00:35:08,921 --> 00:35:11,401
CREATURE: There have been
obstacles.

685
00:35:13,161 --> 00:35:15,961
I told you to be discreet.

686
00:35:16,081 --> 00:35:17,521
CREATURE: We must
remove them all

687
00:35:17,641 --> 00:35:20,201
- immediately.
- No.

688
00:35:23,921 --> 00:35:26,961
CREATURE: The project
must continue as planned.

689
00:35:27,081 --> 00:35:30,161
We must defend.

690
00:35:38,161 --> 00:35:40,801
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

691
00:36:01,161 --> 00:36:03,081
He knows what they are.

692
00:36:03,201 --> 00:36:04,881
Come on, out!

693
00:36:05,001 --> 00:36:06,201
No.

694
00:36:06,321 --> 00:36:08,041
Let's see what else is here.

695
00:36:08,161 --> 00:36:10,121
No. No.

696
00:36:10,241 --> 00:36:13,081
(FIZZING AND CRACKING)

697
00:36:15,321 --> 00:36:17,681
- Yaz!
- CREATURE: Obstacle!

698
00:36:17,801 --> 00:36:19,401
(SCREAMS)

699
00:36:23,841 --> 00:36:25,401
Yaz!

700
00:36:25,521 --> 00:36:27,881
What have you done with her?

701
00:36:28,001 --> 00:36:30,401
Get her back here right now!
Where is she?!

702
00:36:30,521 --> 00:36:32,561
CREATURE: She is gone.

703
00:36:34,361 --> 00:36:36,401
I'm sorry, Yaz.

704
00:36:37,601 --> 00:36:39,681
(GASPS)

705
00:37:05,001 --> 00:37:06,241
OK.

706
00:37:06,361 --> 00:37:07,961
PC Khan.

707
00:37:10,121 --> 00:37:12,161
Nothing to worry about.

708
00:37:33,001 --> 00:37:34,961
(ECHOING) Hello?

709
00:37:36,201 --> 00:37:37,881
Anyone here?

710
00:37:40,041 --> 00:37:41,761
Ryan?!

711
00:37:57,561 --> 00:38:00,121
Interesting.
That glow's increasing.

712
00:38:01,241 --> 00:38:02,841
Life getting more intense...

713
00:38:02,961 --> 00:38:06,481
- O: It's fighting back.
- ...or something going on?

714
00:38:30,921 --> 00:38:32,281
No...

715
00:38:33,521 --> 00:38:35,201
Stay away from me!

716
00:38:39,441 --> 00:38:41,161
What's happening?

717
00:38:46,521 --> 00:38:47,641
This isn't good, Doctor.

718
00:38:47,761 --> 00:38:49,801
It's trying to overload
my system.

719
00:38:49,921 --> 00:38:51,841
(GROANS)

720
00:38:54,481 --> 00:38:56,201
It's like
it's taken a suicide pill!

721
00:38:58,801 --> 00:39:00,601
No.

722
00:39:00,721 --> 00:39:01,921
(SCREAMS)

723
00:39:02,041 --> 00:39:04,081
(ALL GASP)

724
00:39:13,801 --> 00:39:14,601
Yaz!

725
00:39:14,721 --> 00:39:17,641
- Turn the power off in there.
- 0. W's already blown out.

726
00:39:17,761 --> 00:39:20,921
Yaz! How are you even here?

727
00:39:21,041 --> 00:39:22,521
(PHONE RINGS)

728
00:39:25,521 --> 00:39:27,081
Doctor, you've got to help!

729
00:39:27,201 --> 00:39:28,761
I've lost Yaz!

730
00:39:28,881 --> 00:39:31,121
Yaz? I've got her.

731
00:39:31,241 --> 00:39:32,641
We're coming for you now.

732
00:40:06,321 --> 00:40:08,281
You OK?

733
00:40:10,321 --> 00:40:11,961
You get any sleep?

734
00:40:16,881 --> 00:40:18,081
What happened to you?

735
00:40:21,801 --> 00:40:23,321
Don't know.

736
00:40:26,361 --> 00:40:27,881
It were just like...

737
00:40:29,201 --> 00:40:30,521
...nothingness.

738
00:40:31,761 --> 00:40:33,401
Nowhere.

739
00:40:34,721 --> 00:40:36,481
And I was totally alone.

740
00:40:42,441 --> 00:40:44,081
I was so scared.

741
00:40:45,561 --> 00:40:47,001
Ryan...

742
00:40:48,401 --> 00:40:50,121
...I thought I was dead.

743
00:40:54,161 --> 00:40:55,441
Nah.

744
00:40:56,641 --> 00:40:58,761
I'm never going
to let that happen to you.

745
00:41:13,121 --> 00:41:15,761
GRAHAM: You chose
to exile yourself here?

746
00:41:15,881 --> 00:41:18,601
- Yeah.
- Ta.

747
00:41:18,721 --> 00:41:20,721
Thanks. You never get lonely?

748
00:41:20,841 --> 00:41:22,441
Yeah.

749
00:41:22,561 --> 00:41:24,681
- But it's for the best.
- Right.

750
00:41:27,161 --> 00:41:29,121
How long have you known
the Doctor, Graham?

751
00:41:29,241 --> 00:41:31,441
Oh, it's a tricky one
to answer, that. You see,

752
00:41:31,561 --> 00:41:34,041
things never really happen in
a straight line with the Doc.

753
00:41:34,161 --> 00:41:35,641
How much do you know about her?

754
00:41:35,761 --> 00:41:37,001
A bit.

755
00:41:37,121 --> 00:41:40,841
Our paths crossed very briefly
once, when she was a man.

756
00:41:40,961 --> 00:41:43,281
- When she was a what?
- Has she never mentioned that?

757
00:41:43,401 --> 00:41:44,921
I thought she was joking!

758
00:41:45,041 --> 00:41:47,481
You got any idea
where she's from?

759
00:41:47,601 --> 00:41:48,641
Well, we've tried to ask,

760
00:41:48,761 --> 00:41:50,601
but she just changes
the subject, you know?

761
00:41:50,721 --> 00:41:54,561
I've got a whole shelf over
there all about the Doctor.

762
00:41:54,681 --> 00:41:56,241
Everything I could gather.

763
00:41:56,361 --> 00:41:58,481
A lot of inconsistencies,

764
00:41:58,601 --> 00:42:01,041
but it's very,
very interesting.

765
00:42:02,641 --> 00:42:04,481
Do you want to have a look?

766
00:42:06,121 --> 00:42:07,801
(DOOR OPENS)

767
00:42:07,921 --> 00:42:09,481
Come on, you two.

768
00:42:09,601 --> 00:42:12,481
Everyone out front. Lots to
catch up on. I made iced tea.

769
00:42:12,601 --> 00:42:14,561
Possibly.

770
00:42:18,641 --> 00:42:23,041
Daniel Barton's DNA
registers as 93% human.

771
00:42:23,161 --> 00:42:24,881
Which makes him, what, alien?

772
00:42:25,001 --> 00:42:28,521
No, it can't be. I've been
through Barton's records.

773
00:42:28,641 --> 00:42:31,041
There are thousands of photos
of him online at all ages.

774
00:42:31,161 --> 00:42:32,081
If he's not human,

775
00:42:32,201 --> 00:42:34,241
that's one very impressive
legend he's put together.

776
00:42:34,361 --> 00:42:35,561
Not impossible, though.

777
00:42:35,681 --> 00:42:37,641
All right, MI6,
help me with something,

778
00:42:37,761 --> 00:42:39,201
cos I can't get me nut
round it.

779
00:42:39,321 --> 00:42:42,521
C told us that Barton's company

780
00:42:42,641 --> 00:42:44,601
is more powerful
than most countries.

781
00:42:44,721 --> 00:42:45,721
That can't be true.

782
00:42:45,841 --> 00:42:47,801
Governments these days
are full of people

783
00:42:47,921 --> 00:42:49,561
who don't understand
technology,

784
00:42:49,681 --> 00:42:51,601
so countries rely
on outsourcing

785
00:42:51,721 --> 00:42:53,401
their tech requirements
and expertise

786
00:42:53,521 --> 00:42:56,801
to private companies that
transcend national boundaries.

787
00:42:56,921 --> 00:42:58,681
Companies like VOR.

788
00:43:00,121 --> 00:43:03,401
VOR seeps into every corner
of modern technology.

789
00:43:03,521 --> 00:43:06,681
We're talking leisure,
commercial, military.

790
00:43:06,801 --> 00:43:09,881
It leads the way
on face-tagging,

791
00:43:10,001 --> 00:43:11,881
bio data, robotics.

792
00:43:12,001 --> 00:43:13,921
And then there's all
the military systems

793
00:43:14,041 --> 00:43:16,961
across the globe which rely
on servers operated by VOR.

794
00:43:17,081 --> 00:43:20,121
So do we think Barton's behind
the assassination of C?

795
00:43:20,241 --> 00:43:22,641
And the attacking of us
in the car?

796
00:43:22,761 --> 00:43:25,121
Andie in league
with these aliens?

797
00:43:25,241 --> 00:43:27,481
What did he say to
those creatures in his office?

798
00:43:27,601 --> 00:43:28,881
That they should have been
discreet.

799
00:43:29,001 --> 00:43:30,721
So it was like he was
in control of them?

800
00:43:30,841 --> 00:43:32,881
I couldn't work out
who's in charge of who.

801
00:43:33,001 --> 00:43:34,441
(LAPTOP BEEPS)

802
00:43:34,561 --> 00:43:37,481
Ah, found something.

803
00:43:37,601 --> 00:43:39,521
I've been searching
through all the data

804
00:43:39,641 --> 00:43:41,721
you took from Barton
for any codes

805
00:43:41,841 --> 00:43:43,721
or languages
not of this planet,

806
00:43:43,841 --> 00:43:45,361
and it's found something.

807
00:43:45,481 --> 00:43:47,281
In the furthest corner

808
00:43:47,401 --> 00:43:51,521
of the smallest system
of the most obscure company

809
00:43:51,641 --> 00:43:53,201
in Barton's empire -

810
00:43:53,321 --> 00:43:55,561
alien code!

811
00:43:55,681 --> 00:43:57,081
Just decrypting.

812
00:43:57,201 --> 00:43:59,321
Running about 90 billion
possible languages.

813
00:44:02,041 --> 00:44:03,281
Ah.

814
00:44:03,401 --> 00:44:04,601
Nothing.

815
00:44:04,721 --> 00:44:06,281
That can't be right.

816
00:44:06,401 --> 00:44:09,481
I've checked it against every
known language in the universe

817
00:44:09,601 --> 00:44:11,401
and there's no match.

818
00:44:11,521 --> 00:44:12,681
Ah, wait!

819
00:44:12,801 --> 00:44:15,241
I keep the TARDIS systems open
for new languages,

820
00:44:15,361 --> 00:44:17,841
even on the fringes
of the known universe.

821
00:44:17,961 --> 00:44:19,001
If I can synch that...

822
00:44:19,121 --> 00:44:21,761
Bingo! Right, we need
a dark wall. Come on!

823
00:44:24,961 --> 00:44:26,361
RYAN: What is that?

824
00:44:26,481 --> 00:44:30,321
Not sure. A single image
encrypted in alien code.

825
00:44:30,441 --> 00:44:31,921
Trying to decode.

826
00:44:32,041 --> 00:44:33,601
One image, though.

827
00:44:33,721 --> 00:44:35,121
Steganography.

828
00:44:35,241 --> 00:44:38,481
Like what he sent you -
a picture of a fish?

829
00:44:38,601 --> 00:44:39,841
I can't see a pattern
at all, Doc.

830
00:44:39,961 --> 00:44:42,081
Decoding takes a moment.

831
00:44:42,201 --> 00:44:43,561
(SONIC BUZZES)

832
00:44:44,721 --> 00:44:46,201
RYAN: What's that?
Join the dots?

833
00:44:47,721 --> 00:44:50,241
I think it's coordinates.

834
00:44:50,361 --> 00:44:52,601
Coordinates for what?

835
00:44:54,441 --> 00:44:58,001
Locations for those creatures
across planet Earth.

836
00:44:58,121 --> 00:45:01,561
Oh..
That's more than just a few.

837
00:45:04,481 --> 00:45:06,721
There's hundreds of 'em.

838
00:45:06,841 --> 00:45:08,681
We can't deal with all those.

839
00:45:09,881 --> 00:45:11,801
What are they doing here,
anyway?

840
00:45:14,841 --> 00:45:16,881
It's all in the patterns.

841
00:45:17,001 --> 00:45:21,481
Steganography, encrypted code,
attacks on intelligence agents.

842
00:45:21,601 --> 00:45:23,201
It's all spy craft!

843
00:45:23,321 --> 00:45:26,841
They're alien spies
embedded here on Earth!

844
00:45:28,561 --> 00:45:30,001
No, that's not possible.

845
00:45:30,121 --> 00:45:32,121
- Spies from where?
- I don't know.

846
00:45:32,241 --> 00:45:34,321
I don't recognise them.
I don't recognise the language.

847
00:45:34,441 --> 00:45:35,681
Or why
they're attacking people.

848
00:45:35,801 --> 00:45:37,241
Or what happened to you.

849
00:45:37,361 --> 00:45:39,881
The image is still changing,
Doc.

850
00:45:40,001 --> 00:45:42,361
More layers
still being decrypted.

851
00:45:42,481 --> 00:45:44,441
Oh...

852
00:45:44,561 --> 00:45:46,601
Why's it doing that?

853
00:45:46,721 --> 00:45:48,321
I don't understand.

854
00:45:48,441 --> 00:45:50,601
Multiple Earths -
what does that even mean?

855
00:45:50,721 --> 00:45:53,481
OK. OK. If you really think
they're spies,

856
00:45:53,601 --> 00:45:56,241
we should be asking,
"Who's the spymaster?

857
00:45:56,361 --> 00:45:57,721
"Who's running
the alien spies?”

858
00:45:57,841 --> 00:46:00,081
Because that's the person
who holds the answers.

859
00:46:00,201 --> 00:46:01,641
That's got to be
that Daniel Barton, right?

860
00:46:01,761 --> 00:46:04,961
C said they thought Barton
was a double or triple agent.

861
00:46:05,081 --> 00:46:06,361
We need to pay Barton a visit.

862
00:46:06,481 --> 00:46:09,481
Good thing he's having a party,
then. We got invites.

863
00:46:09,601 --> 00:46:11,521
Yes! Nice work, you two.

864
00:46:11,641 --> 00:46:13,561
Got invites for us all,
have you?

865
00:46:13,681 --> 00:46:16,201
I'm sure I can hack a guest
list. What do you reckon, O?

866
00:46:16,321 --> 00:46:17,841
Fancy a trip in the box?

867
00:46:19,881 --> 00:46:21,961
I really, really would.

868
00:46:23,521 --> 00:46:24,961
Be my guest.

869
00:46:30,681 --> 00:46:32,601
Shut up!

870
00:46:37,201 --> 00:46:39,001
Ridiculous.

871
00:46:39,121 --> 00:46:40,361
Somewhere
in the lower substrata

872
00:46:40,481 --> 00:46:41,561
there's a wardrobe hall.

873
00:46:41,681 --> 00:46:43,841
I think it's the first right
after the karaoke buses.

874
00:46:43,961 --> 00:46:45,761
What do we need a wardrobe for?

875
00:46:53,281 --> 00:46:54,521
Shall we?

876
00:47:25,681 --> 00:47:28,121
The name's Doctor. The Doctor.

877
00:47:28,241 --> 00:47:30,601
- We're on the list.
- Welcome. Go right on in.

878
00:47:36,521 --> 00:47:38,761
Thanks for coming.

879
00:47:41,561 --> 00:47:42,841
Is this a bad time to mention

880
00:47:42,961 --> 00:47:44,961
I've never really done
undercover work?

881
00:47:45,081 --> 00:47:48,401
- You said you worked for MI6!
- As an analyst. In the office.

882
00:47:48,521 --> 00:47:50,761
It's a party. We're guests.
Blend in.

883
00:47:50,881 --> 00:47:53,361
And keep an eye out
for Daniel Barton.

884
00:47:56,641 --> 00:47:58,881
YAZ: That should download
every piece of data

885
00:47:59,001 --> 00:48:00,281
his computer
has ever had access to.

886
00:48:00,401 --> 00:48:01,721
Thanks, Anya.

887
00:48:01,841 --> 00:48:04,881
RYAN: Red seven!
Put it on red seven.

888
00:48:05,001 --> 00:48:07,881
- Lucky number seven.
- GRAHAM: All of it?

889
00:48:08,001 --> 00:48:10,241
- CROUPIER: No more bets.
- You'd better be right. Seven.

890
00:48:11,321 --> 00:48:13,281
CROUPIER: Seven.

891
00:48:13,401 --> 00:48:15,401
RYAN: Get in!

892
00:48:15,521 --> 00:48:17,001
I'm rich!

893
00:48:17,121 --> 00:48:18,761
Good evening, ladies.

894
00:48:18,881 --> 00:48:20,281
That's my grandson.

895
00:48:20,401 --> 00:48:22,361
Seven! Get it!

896
00:48:22,481 --> 00:48:24,041
Card.

897
00:48:25,081 --> 00:48:26,481
Card.

898
00:48:26,601 --> 00:48:28,241
Card.

899
00:48:29,361 --> 00:48:30,681
Snap!

900
00:48:30,801 --> 00:48:32,241
(GUESTS LAUGH)

901
00:48:33,681 --> 00:48:35,121
Is that not the game?

902
00:48:41,241 --> 00:48:43,361
- Did we win?
- No.

903
00:48:43,481 --> 00:48:44,761
Didn't know
what I was doing anyway.

904
00:48:44,881 --> 00:48:48,721
You know what they say -
lucky at dice, unlucky in love.

905
00:48:48,841 --> 00:48:51,481
- Do they say that?
- No.

906
00:48:52,601 --> 00:48:54,241
(DOOR OPENS)

907
00:49:02,041 --> 00:49:03,921
Time for a chat.

908
00:49:10,081 --> 00:49:12,281
Nice party.

909
00:49:12,401 --> 00:49:14,081
Nice house.

910
00:49:14,201 --> 00:49:16,281
Daniel. I don't think
we've been introduced.

911
00:49:16,401 --> 00:49:17,801
I'm the Doctor.

912
00:49:17,921 --> 00:49:20,041
I'm a plus-one.

913
00:49:20,161 --> 00:49:22,801
So, did you assassinate
the head of MI6 yourself,

914
00:49:22,921 --> 00:49:24,401
or just order it?

915
00:49:24,521 --> 00:49:27,201
I think
you're at the wrong party.

916
00:49:27,321 --> 00:49:30,281
Casino theme, not whodunnit.

917
00:49:30,401 --> 00:49:31,401
Why is there an alien code

918
00:49:31,521 --> 00:49:33,521
embedded at the edge
of your company's systems?

919
00:49:34,641 --> 00:49:37,641
We both know you're in league
with a race of alien creatures.

920
00:49:37,761 --> 00:49:40,721
I think you'd better get your
medication checked, Doctor,

921
00:49:40,841 --> 00:49:42,241
or maybe some psychiatric help,

922
00:49:42,361 --> 00:49:43,801
because I don't know
who you are

923
00:49:43,921 --> 00:49:45,881
or what you're talking about.

924
00:49:46,001 --> 00:49:48,201
How long have they been here?

925
00:49:48,321 --> 00:49:50,201
Where are they from?

926
00:49:50,321 --> 00:49:51,521
Who recruited whom?

927
00:49:51,641 --> 00:49:53,721
Are you running them,
or are they running you?

928
00:49:53,841 --> 00:49:58,121
Why is your DNA 7% non-human?

929
00:49:59,561 --> 00:50:01,561
You're properly unhinged.

930
00:50:01,681 --> 00:50:03,041
No. I'm onto you,

931
00:50:03,161 --> 00:50:05,321
and1'm going to stop you.

932
00:50:06,441 --> 00:50:07,801
I'm going to walk away now

933
00:50:07,921 --> 00:50:09,921
and you're going
to stay away from me

934
00:50:10,041 --> 00:50:11,681
for the rest of both our lives,

935
00:50:11,801 --> 00:50:14,601
either voluntarily or because
of my security people.

936
00:50:14,721 --> 00:50:16,041
Understand?

937
00:50:17,361 --> 00:50:18,961
I'm really hard to get rid of,
Mr Barton.

938
00:50:20,081 --> 00:50:21,201
Are you?

939
00:50:27,601 --> 00:50:29,521
Barton's heading your way,
gang.

940
00:50:29,641 --> 00:50:30,561
Keep an eye on him.

941
00:50:30,681 --> 00:50:32,521
Don't let him
out of your sight.

942
00:50:35,281 --> 00:50:37,601
None of you saw him
come back in?

943
00:50:37,721 --> 00:50:39,601
- He must be here somewhere.
- There he is!

944
00:50:41,601 --> 00:50:43,521
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

945
00:50:43,641 --> 00:50:45,161
Oh, no, you don't.

946
00:50:46,321 --> 00:50:48,201
(TYRES SCREECH)

947
00:50:49,881 --> 00:50:51,601
GRAHAM: He's off!

948
00:50:51,721 --> 00:50:54,641
RYAN: I mean, who leaves
their own birthday party?

949
00:50:54,761 --> 00:50:56,481
He's definitely guilty.

950
00:50:56,601 --> 00:50:57,921
So what do we do now?

951
00:50:58,041 --> 00:51:01,281
Remember our trip to
the Great Kalisperon Bike-Off?

952
00:51:11,481 --> 00:51:15,201
Sir, it seems we have three of
your motorcycles following us.

953
00:51:16,441 --> 00:51:17,961
What exactly do I pay you for?

954
00:51:25,401 --> 00:51:27,721
- Go, go, go, go!
- I'm going! I'm going!

955
00:51:34,161 --> 00:51:36,681
- (GUNSHOT)
- (LAUGHS)

956
00:51:36,801 --> 00:51:38,521
(GUNSHOTS)

957
00:51:38,641 --> 00:51:42,481
- Hey! He's shooting at us!
- Yes, I got that!

958
00:52:00,921 --> 00:52:02,521
Oh!

959
00:52:02,641 --> 00:52:04,641
Is this what it's like
being with the Doctor?

960
00:52:04,761 --> 00:52:06,601
(YELLS)

961
00:52:06,721 --> 00:52:10,081
Mate, this is one
of the quiet days! Agh!

962
00:52:25,081 --> 00:52:26,961
What now?

963
00:52:27,081 --> 00:52:28,801
(HANGAR DOOR BANGS SHUT)

964
00:52:28,921 --> 00:52:31,561
(SONIC BUZZES)

965
00:52:46,561 --> 00:52:49,281
- BARTON: She ready to go?
- All secure, Mr Barton.

966
00:52:50,841 --> 00:52:52,681
How many planes
does one guy need?

967
00:52:52,801 --> 00:52:54,401
There he is.

968
00:53:01,881 --> 00:53:04,001
- That's one big plane.
- Where's he going in that?

969
00:53:04,121 --> 00:53:05,921
I don't know,
but we can't let him get away.

970
00:53:06,041 --> 00:53:06,961
How? It's not as if we're gonna

971
00:53:07,081 --> 00:53:09,441
just jump on a plane
with him, is it?

972
00:53:09,561 --> 00:53:10,961
Aww, come on!

973
00:53:11,081 --> 00:53:12,721
(SIGHS)

974
00:53:12,841 --> 00:53:15,081
Lonsdale tower,
Barton one-niner,

975
00:53:15,201 --> 00:53:16,401
request clearance.

976
00:53:16,521 --> 00:53:18,761
- (SONIC BUZZES)
- Oh!

977
00:53:22,361 --> 00:53:23,921
(GROANS)

978
00:53:24,041 --> 00:53:26,441
COMMS: Cleared to Hawkston
radar vectors to Skaggs Island,

979
00:53:26,561 --> 00:53:30,081
- then as filed. Squawk 4634.
- (CONTROL PANEL BEEPS)

980
00:53:30,201 --> 00:53:32,161
She's in!

981
00:53:32,281 --> 00:53:35,521
- (SONIC BUZZES)
- Fix alert sensors.

982
00:53:38,041 --> 00:53:40,841
- Agh!
- I've got you, Yaz.

983
00:53:40,961 --> 00:53:43,401
COMMS: Barton one-niner,
climb 3,000 feet

984
00:53:43,521 --> 00:53:46,001
maintain runway heading.
Cleared for takeoff.

985
00:53:46,121 --> 00:53:48,401
- Runway zero one.
- Cleared for takeoff.

986
00:53:48,521 --> 00:53:50,921
Runway zero one.
Maintain runway heading.

987
00:53:51,041 --> 00:53:54,081
Climb 3,000 feet,
Barton one-niner.

988
00:53:54,201 --> 00:53:56,761
(PHONE RINGS)

989
00:53:56,881 --> 00:53:59,081
- Hey, where are you going?
- Come on, son!

990
00:53:59,201 --> 00:54:01,481
I need to close the door!

991
00:54:04,481 --> 00:54:07,121
Sorry. I've never been good
at sprinting.

992
00:54:07,241 --> 00:54:08,201
What?!

993
00:54:08,321 --> 00:54:10,201
Come on, Doctor.
We're about to take off.

994
00:54:10,321 --> 00:54:12,841
In the main cabin!

995
00:54:12,961 --> 00:54:14,561
(SONIC BUZZES)

996
00:54:23,561 --> 00:54:24,481
Here...

997
00:54:24,601 --> 00:54:25,761
YAZ: What are we
actually going to do?

998
00:54:25,881 --> 00:54:27,601
Sit tight.

999
00:54:27,721 --> 00:54:29,281
See where he's going.

1000
00:54:30,841 --> 00:54:31,881
Never been good at sprinting?

1001
00:54:32,001 --> 00:54:34,601
I was the last one
in every race at school.

1002
00:54:34,721 --> 00:54:36,281
No, no, no. I read your file.

1003
00:54:36,401 --> 00:54:38,761
You were a champion sprinter.

1004
00:54:40,081 --> 00:54:41,481
Mmm.

1005
00:54:44,961 --> 00:54:46,321
Got me.

1006
00:54:46,441 --> 00:54:47,521
Well done.

1007
00:54:48,881 --> 00:54:51,601
- GRAHAM: What's going on, Doc?
- I don't know.

1008
00:54:53,321 --> 00:54:55,321
You'd best take a look
out of the window.

1009
00:55:00,081 --> 00:55:02,601
GRAHAM: How's your house
out there?

1010
00:55:02,721 --> 00:55:05,281
Bit Wicked Witch of the West,
but you get the gist.

1011
00:55:05,401 --> 00:55:07,281
Maybe. Maybe not.

1012
00:55:07,401 --> 00:55:08,961
No...

1013
00:55:09,081 --> 00:55:11,241
Oh, come on, Doctor, catch up.

1014
00:55:11,361 --> 00:55:12,961
You can do it.

1015
00:55:13,081 --> 00:55:15,161
Ohh...

1016
00:55:15,281 --> 00:55:19,121
That's...that's my name,
and that is why I chose it.

1017
00:55:20,881 --> 00:55:23,721
So satisfying.

1018
00:55:23,841 --> 00:55:27,361
Doctor, I did say
look for the spymaster.

1019
00:55:27,481 --> 00:55:29,601
Or should I say spy...

1020
00:55:31,161 --> 00:55:32,721
...Master?

1021
00:55:37,481 --> 00:55:39,241
Hi.

1022
00:55:39,361 --> 00:55:41,401
You can't be...

1023
00:55:41,521 --> 00:55:43,201
Oh, I can be. I very much am.

1024
00:55:44,481 --> 00:55:47,081
So what's going on, then?
He's not really 0?

1025
00:55:47,201 --> 00:55:49,081
I'm her best enemy.

1026
00:55:50,441 --> 00:55:52,121
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

1027
00:55:52,241 --> 00:55:53,801
- Call me Master.
- GRAHAM: Call you what?

1028
00:55:53,921 --> 00:55:54,841
"Master"?

1029
00:55:54,961 --> 00:55:58,761
Me and her,
we go way, way, way back.

1030
00:55:58,881 --> 00:56:00,641
- I met O!
- I know.

1031
00:56:00,761 --> 00:56:03,441
- Years ago.
- I know!

1032
00:56:03,561 --> 00:56:04,601
(CACKLES)

1033
00:56:04,721 --> 00:56:06,081
But there was an O at MI6.

1034
00:56:06,201 --> 00:56:07,881
- C was talking about him.
- Yeah.

1035
00:56:08,001 --> 00:56:10,641
A man very close to my heart.

1036
00:56:11,721 --> 00:56:13,841
Well, in my pocket, actually.

1037
00:56:13,961 --> 00:56:14,881
Do you want to see him?

1038
00:56:15,001 --> 00:56:16,721
It's always good to keep
a backup of one's work.

1039
00:56:16,841 --> 00:56:20,041
Tissue compression
is a classic.

1040
00:56:20,161 --> 00:56:21,601
Ohh...

1041
00:56:25,601 --> 00:56:28,761
Ambushed him on his way to work
for his first day.

1042
00:56:28,881 --> 00:56:33,041
Shrunk him, took his identity
and set myself up in MI6.

1043
00:56:34,641 --> 00:56:36,721
Surprisingly good
staff canteen.

1044
00:56:40,161 --> 00:56:44,161
I have had a lot of fun.

1045
00:56:45,521 --> 00:56:47,081
I need to warn Barton!

1046
00:56:48,681 --> 00:56:50,281
He's not here!

1047
00:56:50,401 --> 00:56:53,041
Where's Barton?
What have you done to him?

1048
00:56:53,161 --> 00:56:54,361
Barton!

1049
00:56:54,481 --> 00:56:56,641
GRAHAM: Who's flying the plane?

1050
00:56:56,761 --> 00:56:59,081
Wrong question. Check the seat.

1051
00:56:59,201 --> 00:57:01,241
(BEEPING)

1052
00:57:05,201 --> 00:57:07,401
Cockpit bomb.

1053
00:57:07,521 --> 00:57:09,441
Short fuse.

1054
00:57:09,561 --> 00:57:11,281
I can relate to that!

1055
00:57:12,441 --> 00:57:14,761
- (SONIC BUZZES)
- Now, do you really think

1056
00:57:14,881 --> 00:57:18,081
that I would not make that
sonic-proof, Doctor?

1057
00:57:18,201 --> 00:57:19,321
Come on!

1058
00:57:20,561 --> 00:57:22,441
Deadlock sealed.

1059
00:57:22,561 --> 00:57:25,681
And I made sure -
no parachutes on board.

1060
00:57:25,801 --> 00:57:27,561
There must be a way!

1061
00:57:27,681 --> 00:57:30,201
(GASPS) OK. OK.

1062
00:57:31,681 --> 00:57:33,281
But where's Barton?
We saw him coming in.

1063
00:57:33,401 --> 00:57:36,281
Called away before takeoff.
By me!

1064
00:57:36,401 --> 00:57:38,721
Stick with me, Yaz,
cos I control...

1065
00:57:40,721 --> 00:57:42,241
...everything.

1066
00:57:42,361 --> 00:57:43,801
Even these guys.

1067
00:57:43,921 --> 00:57:46,041
(WHISTLES)

1068
00:57:46,161 --> 00:57:48,241
(FIZZING AND CRACKING)

1069
00:57:49,561 --> 00:57:51,641
(LAUGHS MANIACALLY)

1070
00:57:51,761 --> 00:57:52,681
Yes!

1071
00:57:52,801 --> 00:57:55,201
I can't do it!

1072
00:57:55,321 --> 00:57:56,601
Get away!

1073
00:58:01,401 --> 00:58:03,441
Yah!

1074
00:58:04,881 --> 00:58:06,161
(SCREAMS)

1075
00:58:08,761 --> 00:58:12,321
One last thing.
Something you should know

1076
00:58:12,441 --> 00:58:15,401
in the seconds
before you die...

1077
00:58:16,881 --> 00:58:19,241
Everything that you think
you know...

1078
00:58:20,681 --> 00:58:22,081
...is a lie.

1079
00:58:23,601 --> 00:58:27,041
Got you...finally.

1080
00:58:33,201 --> 00:58:35,361
(ALL SCREAM)

1081
00:58:39,641 --> 00:58:42,081
- (GASPS)
- (AUDIO SLOWS)

1082
00:58:48,721 --> 00:58:50,041
No...

1083
00:58:51,761 --> 00:58:53,281
No, no, no, no, no.

1084
00:59:33,401 --> 00:59:34,201
(BEEPS)

1085
00:59:34,321 --> 00:59:36,281
A little chaos
is a wonderful thing.

1086
00:59:36,401 --> 00:59:39,561
When I arrange for your death,
I expect you to stay dead.

1087
00:59:41,201 --> 00:59:43,361
Welcome
to the end of your lives.

